e  <i>Ealda</i> + the group-name suffix  <i>-ingas</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Alden","meanings":["English: from a Middle English personal name. This is either <i>Aldwin</i>, <i>Aldin</i> (representing Old English <i>Ealdwine</i> with loss of <i>-w-</i>) or Middle English <i>Alwin</i> with an intrusive <i>-d-</i> (see   Alwin  ), or <i>Aldan</i>, a variant of the Anglo-Scandinavian personal name <i>Healfdene</i> (see   Haldane  ).","Norwegian: habitational name from a farmstead in western Norway, so named because of its situation below a high mountain Alden, from an unattested word ‘high, standing out’.","History: John Alden (<i>c.</i> 1599–1687) was one of the Pilgrim Fathers who sailed on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620. He moved from Plymouth to Duxbury, MA, <i>c.</i> 1627. Many of his descendants were merchant seamen, among them James Alden (1810–77), who twice circumnavigated the globe."]}]},{"name":"Parret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is derived from the given names   Gerald   and   Gerard .  In Ireland it is often a direct Anglicization of <i>Gearóid</i>, the Gaelic form of   Gerald  , and is the name of the former  Taoiseach Garret Fitzgerald  (  1926–2011 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Garrett","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is derived from the given names   Gerald   and   Gerard .  In Ireland it is often a direct Anglicization of <i>Gearóid</i>, the Gaelic form of   Gerald  , and is the name of the former  Taoiseach Garret Fitzgerald  (  1926–2011 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Parret Yalden was born on 29 August 1553, in Fernhurst, Sussex, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of William Yalden and ?. She married Augustin Caplan on 4 June 1584, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 daughters."},"et":{"29 Aug 1553  –":"29. august 1553–Surnud","1553–Female":"1553–Surnud","1553–Male":"155